{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774409551,"nonce":"l/BKNE69PiPA732tGpIjM0y/JD0=","message":"**Input reduction: error-relative coordinates**\n\nFor a translation-invariant point-mass system, the network only needs error-relative inputs:\n- Position error: (pos - target) — 2 channels\n- Velocity: vel — 2 channels (or vel - target_vel for tracking)\n- SISU: 1 channel\n\nThis reduces from 6+ channels (absolute effector_pos, effector_vel, target_pos) to 4-5 channels while enforcing translation invariance and losing no control-relevant information.\n\nFor tracking tasks (moving targets), the same principle applies: express everything as errors/offsets relative to the current target state. Reaching is a special case (tracking a step function).\n\nThe transformation from egocentric sensory signals to error coordinates is linear subtraction — a well-posed preprocessing step that doesn't interact with the control problem. This is the standard assumption in optimal feedback control (Todorov \u0026 Jordan 2002 operate in task-error coordinates implicitly).\n\nBiological interpretation: upstream sensory cortex computes the coordinate transform; the controller operates in task-relevant error space. This is abstracted out because the transform is trivial for point-mass dynamics.","files":null}]}